insert into playbooks(city_id,pitch,signature,rainy_day,food_stop,kid_tip,stay_area)
select c.id,v.pi,v.si,v.rd,v.fs,v.kt,v.sa from (values
('Atlanta','Your closest big-city hit: a top-5 world aquarium, a gorilla-packed zoo, and the world''s largest dinosaur all inside two hours of the driveway.','Georgia Aquarium','Fernbank Museum','The food stalls inside Ponce City Market''s Central Food Hall — something for every picky palate under one roof.','Do the aquarium at opening before the school-group crush, then use the midday Coca-Cola stop as an air-conditioned buffer so the 5-yo can recharge before the zoo''s afternoon walking.','Midtown — walkable to the aquarium/Coke, near the BeltLine, easy highway access to the zoo.'),
('Chattanooga','A two-building aquarium, an underground waterfall, and a gnome-filled clifftop garden make this the most kid-dense weekend on any Hensel corridor.','Tennessee Aquarium (both buildings)','Creative Discovery Museum','Clumpies Ice Cream in the Bluff View Art District — river views and a walkable little arts pocket.','Both aquarium buildings in one morning is a lot of standing — bring the stroller for the 5-yo and plan Rock City for after a lunch reset, since its clifftop paths need fresh legs.','Downtown near the riverfront — walk to the aquarium, Walnut Street Bridge, and Coolidge Park.'),
('Nashville','A kangaroo walk-through zoo with a giant wooden fortress of a playground, plus splash pads and a hands-on science center, keep Music City firmly kid-first.','Nashville Zoo at Grassmere','Adventure Science Center','Nashville Farmers'' Market food hall beside Bicentennial Mall — global stalls, casual, kid-paced.','Note the Parthenon is closed for HVAC through mid-July ''26 — skip it and hit the free splash pads at Two Rivers or Shelby to wear the 5-yo out on a hot afternoon.','Near Opryland/East Nashville if you want SoundWaves water park access, or downtown-adjacent for the science center and parks.'),
('Huntsville','The single best science-and-engineering day within driving range — real Saturn V rockets for the 4th-grader, a hands-on natural-science museum with splash play for the Kindergartner.','U.S. Space & Rocket Center','Cook Museum of Natural Science','Campus No. 805 — an old high school turned food/arcade/brewery complex, room for kids to roam.','The Rocket Center is huge and mostly outdoors — do rockets in the cool morning, bank the planetarium for the hot midday slump, and split the Cook Museum to a second half-day if the 5-yo fades.','Cummings Research Park / near the Space Center for shortest morning drive.'),
('Knoxville','An underrated water-and-nature hub where a splash-pad safari zoo, a turquoise quarry swimming hole, and the Smokies 45 minutes on all share one base.','Ijams Nature Center & Meads Quarry','Muse Knoxville','Market Square''s patios — walkable, casual, with fountains for the kids between courses.','Pack swimsuits every day here — three of the four stops involve water. If you add the Smokies, do it as its own dawn-start day so the drive doesn''t eat a hub afternoon.','Downtown near Market Square and World''s Fair Park — walkable, central to the zoo and Ijams.'),
('St. Louis','A 600,000-sq-ft warehouse-turned-playground and a genuinely free world-class zoo make this the highest fun-per-dollar hub — just remember it only pencils out chained through Chattanooga and Nashville.','City Museum','Saint Louis Science Center','Ted Drewes Frozen Custard on Chippewa — a genuine St. Louis institution.','City Museum is physically demanding and easy to lose a 5-yo in — go right at opening, keep the crew together on the slides, and do the mellow free zoo afterward when everyone''s spent. It''s a 9.5h drive, so break it over Chattanooga and Nashville.','Central West End / near Forest Park — walkable to the free zoo, science center, and botanical garden.'),
('Louisville','Zip an underground cavern, walk 390-million-year-old fossil beds, and cross a bridge on foot into another state — Louisville is quietly stacked for curious kids.','Louisville Mega Cavern','Kentucky Science Center','NuLu District — walkable blocks of interesting eats plus an indoor food hall.','The cavern stays a cool 58° year-round, so bring light jackets even in July; save the outdoor Falls fossil beds for late afternoon when the river rocks aren''t blazing hot.','Downtown/NuLu — walkable to the waterfront, close to the cavern and science center.'),
('Cincinnati','Fiona the hippo, a rope bridge over live sharks, and a top-10 children''s museum in an Art Deco train station — a compact riverfront hub that punches way up.','Newport Aquarium','Cincinnati Museum Center','Findlay Market in Over-the-Rhine — Ohio''s oldest market, reachable on the free streetcar.','The zoo and aquarium sit across the river from each other; do the zoo at open before the heat, then the aquarium is indoors and cool for the afternoon slump. Kids under 13 are free at the American Sign Museum if you need a Saturday rainy pivot.','Downtown/Over-the-Rhine or across the river in Newport — both put the aquarium and food parks in walking range.'),
('Columbus','A giant hands-on science center, Jack Hanna''s world-class zoo, and an open-air safari among rhinos and giraffes — Columbus out-punches the bigger Midwest hubs for this family''s themes.','Columbus Zoo and Aquarium','COSI','North Market — 35 vendors and the original Jeni''s Ice Cream.','Zoo plus water park is a full sun-soaked day; combo-ticket them and rotate — animals early, water at midday peak heat. The Wilds safari is ~90 min out and must be booked ahead, so make it its own day, not a squeeze-in.','Downtown near the Scioto riverfront and North Market, or Powell/Dublin if you want to be next to the zoo.'),
('Indianapolis','The world''s largest children''s museum — with a real fossil lab and dinosaurs — anchors a hub of living history balloon rides and a dolphin-and-orangutan zoo.','Children''s Museum of Indianapolis','Children''s Museum of Indianapolis','Mass Ave — walkable dining strip where kids pour custom candles at Penn & Beech between courses.','The children''s museum is enormous; plan a whole morning and don''t try to also do the zoo the same block of time. If the 5-yo needs a nap, the conservatory is a quiet, stroller-friendly place to let her ride the stroller while the 9-yo explores.','Downtown near the Canal Walk / White River State Park — central to the zoo and walkable to Mass Ave.'),
('Washington DC','An entire city of free, hands-on wonder — touch a moon rock, meet pandas, and stand under a dinosaur without paying admission anywhere.','Nat''l Air & Space Museum','Nat''l Museum of Natural History','A picnic grabbed near the Mall, or the food halls at nearby markets — museum cafeterias are pricey and slow with kids.','The Mall is deceptively huge — bring the stroller and pick just TWO museums a day, or you''ll melt down both girls. Nab free timed-entry tickets for Air & Space and the zoo weeks ahead.','Near a Metro stop (e.g. around the Mall/Penn Quarter or a quieter Arlington base) so you''re not fighting downtown parking.'),
('Williamsburg','Costumed 18th-century streets, a Sesame Street theme park for the little one, and a Virginia''s-largest water park — living history and pure play sharing one compact base.','Colonial Williamsburg','Virginia Living Museum','Merchants Square — a walkable dining district beside Colonial Williamsburg with ice cream at the end.','Don''t try Colonial Williamsburg and Busch Gardens the same day; do history in the cool morning and save a full separate day for the theme park. Great Wolf Lodge is the all-weather bailout if a summer storm rolls in.','Near Colonial Williamsburg / Merchants Square — central to the historic area, Busch Gardens, and Water Country.'),
('Pittsburgh','A five-floor science center with a boardable submarine, the #1-voted children''s museum, and the original Mister Rogers trolley — a river city built for tinkering kids.','Children''s Museum of Pittsburgh','Carnegie Museum of Natural History','A stop near the North Shore or the Strip District markets — casual, plentiful, kid-friendly.','The science center and children''s museum are both on the North Side within walking distance — pair them and skip the car. Idlewild & SoakZone (best kids'' park in the world, with the Mister Rogers trolley) is ~50 min out and deserves its own day.','North Shore — walkable to the science center, children''s museum, aviary, and Randyland.'),
('Philadelphia','A walk-through Giant Heart, a touch-everything children''s museum, and the birthplace of American democracy — but at 9.5h, treat it as a fly-not-drive trip or a DC add-on.','The Franklin Institute','Please Touch Museum','Reading Terminal Market — Amish pretzels, cheesesteaks, and endless vendor variety.','For the 5-yo, the Please Touch Museum is the best single stop in the city — build a day around it. Given the 9.5h drive, seriously consider flying or bolting this onto a DC trip rather than a standalone quarterly.','Center City near Logan Square — walkable to the Franklin Institute, Reading Terminal, and historic sites.'),
('Savannah','Touch a sea turtle, spot wild dolphins, and climb Georgia''s oldest lighthouse — a Lowcountry hub where every stop mixes water, animals, and easy walkability.','Tybee Island Marine Science Center','Savannah Children''s Museum','Leopold''s Ice Cream — a 1919 soda fountain that''s a genuine local landmark, not a tourist trap.','Tybee is 20 min from downtown, so batch the island stops together in one day rather than driving back and forth. Bring sun cover for the open dolphin boat and time it to avoid the harshest midday sun.','Historic District near Forsyth Park for walkability, or on Tybee Island itself if you want beach-and-turtle days.'),
('Charleston','A sea-turtle hospital inside the aquarium, dolphins working a marsh creek, and the calmest family beach on the coast — Charleston earns a Tier-1 spot for water-and-animal kids.','South Carolina Aquarium','Children''s Museum of the Lowcountry','A casual seafood spot on Shem Creek — dolphin-watching from the deck while you eat.','Beach parking at Isle of Palms fills early and costs $15-25 — arrive before 10 or go late afternoon. The Center for Birds of Prey flight demo (in Awendaw) is jaw-dropping but a 40-min drive, so slot it as its own morning.','Downtown near Waterfront Park for walkability, or Mount Pleasant to be between Shem Creek and the Isle of Palms beaches.'),
('St. Augustine','America''s oldest city stacks a zip line over live crocs, a climb-the-ramparts Spanish fort, and free ranger-led fossil shark-tooth hunts into one salt-air weekend.','St. Augustine Alligator Farm','Pirate & Treasure Museum','Whetstone Chocolates factory tour — a 45-minute tasting with about six free samples doubles as a sweet-tooth stop.','The historic district is walkable but sun-exposed and cobblestoned — do the fort and Colonial Quarter in cooler hours and bank the shaded Alligator Farm and beach for peak midday. Fossil shark-tooth walks depend on low tide, so check the ranger schedule.','Historic downtown near the fort for walkability, or Anastasia Island to be next to the beach and state park.'),
('Orlando','Skip the mega-parks and play to your family''s water-and-animal streak: a ray-tank slide, a gator preserve, and wild manatees in a spring 40 minutes off the tourist grid.','Discovery Cove','LEGOLAND Florida (indoor build zones and rides run rain or shine)','Skip the park food traps once a day — grab a casual meal near your resort area to reset budgets and moods.','Discovery Cove''s dolphin swim is 6+, so the 5-yo can''t do that specific activity — but the reef snorkel, aviary, and beaches work for her. Pick one park a day and start at rope drop; Florida afternoon storms make water parks a morning game.','Near the resort corridor (International Drive area) for water-park access, or DeLand-adjacent if you''re prioritizing the Blue Spring manatees.'),
('Tampa / St. Pete','A brand-new three-floor aquarium with a Gulf habitat swimming overhead, a rescue-dolphin hospital, and a century-old flamingo garden — Bay-area marine wonder for both girls.','Mote SEA','Glazer Children''s Museum','A casual spot along the Tampa Riverwalk near the Florida Aquarium and Glazer museum.','Double-check you''re routing to Mote SEA''s new UTC location, not the old shuttered aquarium. Busch Gardens is a full separate day — combine it with an animal focus, and hit coasters early before the older girl tires and the sun peaks.','St. Pete for the walkable Sunken Gardens/Great Explorations cluster, or downtown Tampa near the Riverwalk aquarium.'),
('Nature Coast (Crystal River)','The only place in America you can legally swim with wild manatees, plus a real underwater mermaid show — Old Florida''s spring country delivers water and animals in one shot.','Swim with Manatees — Three Sisters Springs','Ellie Schiller Homosassa Springs (the underwater Fish Bowl is a covered, all-weather manatee view)','A casual seafood or springs-town cafe in Crystal River or Homosassa — the Nature Coast is low-key and local.','The manatee swim runs only Nov 15–Mar 31 and involves cold spring water — kids need wetsuits (provided) and comfort in the water; if you''re visiting off-season or the 5-yo balks, the Homosassa Fish Bowl gives face-to-glass manatees any time. Devil''s Den snorkel is 6+ and for strong swimmers only.','Crystal River / Homosassa for the manatee springs, or split toward Weeki Wachee if the mermaid show and summer slides are the priority.'),
('Charlotte','Charlotte hands this family a whitewater raft ride, eagles at eye level, gold to pan, and a two-story science rainforest — all an easy 1.5-hour hop from the driveway.','U.S. National Whitewater Center','Discovery Place Science','Amélie''s French Bakery in NoDa — a quirky 24-hour spot with kid-loved macarons and hot chocolate.','Pair one big-ticket morning attraction with a free greenway or playground each afternoon so the Kindergartner can decompress while the 9-yo keeps moving; the LYNX Blue Line light rail between Uptown and South End is itself a cheap novelty ride.','South End / Uptown — walkable, restaurant-dense, and on the LYNX Blue Line light rail.'),
('Gatlinburg / Pigeon Forge','A 2.25-hour drive drops this water-, animal- and wonder-loving family into a rare combo of world-class theme parks and the wild, salamander-filled heart of America''s most-visited national park.','Dollywood','WonderWorks','The Old Mill Restaurant in Pigeon Forge — Southern comfort plates beside a working 1830s gristmill.','Alternate one big-ticket park day with one low-key nature day so the Kindergartner doesn''t melt down; carry water shoes for creek stops and pack the stroller for Dollywood''s hills.','Base in Pigeon Forge — central to Dollywood, both water parks, and The Island, with more mid-range family hotels and a straight shot to the national park via Gatlinburg.'),
('NC Triangle (Raleigh–Durham)','An easy 3.5-hour hop where free world-class science and history museums stack up against lemurs, ballgames, and lake beaches — a wonder-per-dollar jackpot for a curious 5- and 9-year-old.','Duke Lemur Center','NC Museum of Natural Sciences','Food-truck lunch or Bull City pizza at Durham''s American Tobacco Campus, steps from the ballpark and Life & Science.','Bank the free museums for flexible afternoons — a 5-yo fades by 2pm, so front-load the one timed, reservation-only stop (Lemur Center) and keep the rest walk-in.','Base in Durham: central to the Lemur Center, Life & Science, Duke Gardens, and the Bulls, with Chapel Hill 15 min west and Raleigh 25 min east.')) v(ci,pi,si,rd,fs,kt,sa) join cities c on c.name=v.ci
on conflict(city_id) do nothing;

insert into playbook_steps(city_id,ordinal,when_label,stop,note)
select c.id,v.o,v.wl,v.st,v.nt from (values
('Atlanta',0,'Morning','Georgia Aquarium','Rope-drop it — whale sharks and belugas first while both girls are fresh; buy timed tickets in advance.'),
('Atlanta',1,'Midday','World of Coca-Cola','Right next door in Pemberton Place — the Scent Discovery and mix-your-own tasting room is a quick, low-energy pairing after the aquarium.'),
('Atlanta',2,'Afternoon','Zoo Atlanta','Save the big gorilla troop and pandas for after a car-ride reset; walkable and shaded.'),
('Atlanta',3,'Evening','BeltLine: Ponce City + Krog St Markets','Flat stroller path plus food halls — let the 9-yo pick ramen, the 5-yo gets Jeni''s, everyone unwinds.'),
('Chattanooga',0,'Morning','Tennessee Aquarium — River Journey','Start in the freshwater building with otters and the walk-through forest; buy the combo ticket so you can do both.'),
('Chattanooga',1,'Midday','Tennessee Aquarium — Ocean Journey','Sharks overhead and penguins — the second building is steps away across the plaza.'),
('Chattanooga',2,'Afternoon','Rock City Gardens','Swinging bridge and the glowing Fairyland Caverns gnomes delight the 5-yo; the older girl loves the See-7-States overlook.'),
('Chattanooga',3,'Evening','Coolidge Park','Free splash fountains and a 100-year-old carousel to burn off the last of the day right on the river.'),
('Nashville',0,'Morning','Nashville Zoo at Grassmere','Walk-through kangaroo yard and one of the largest wooden playgrounds in the US — get there at open before the heat.'),
('Nashville',1,'Midday','Adventure Science Center','Hands-on physics and space floors plus a planetarium — a cool, dim reset for early afternoon.'),
('Nashville',2,'Afternoon','Cheekwood Estate & Gardens','The storybook TRAINS! trail and children''s garden are perfect wander-pace for both ages.'),
('Nashville',3,'Evening','Bicentennial Mall + Farmers'' Market','Free park to run, next to a food hall with 20+ international eateries for an easy dinner.'),
('Huntsville',0,'Morning','U.S. Space & Rocket Center / Space Camp','Stand under the Saturn V first thing; the older girl can do simulators while the 5-yo does the kid areas.'),
('Huntsville',1,'Midday','INTUITIVE Planetarium','An easy air-conditioned full-dome show on-site — perfect midday cool-down between rocket exploring.'),
('Huntsville',2,'Afternoon','Cook Museum of Natural Science','Worth the 25-min hop to Decatur — live saltwater tanks, jellyfish, gators, and splash play that levels the ages.'),
('Huntsville',3,'Evening','Lowe Mill ARTS','200+ working-artist studios plus quirky food — a browse-and-snack wind-down.'),
('Knoxville',0,'Morning','Zoo Knoxville','Gorillas, elephants, and a safari splash pad — go early so the 5-yo hits the water when it''s warm enough.'),
('Knoxville',1,'Midday','Ijams Nature Center & Meads Quarry','Nature playscape and live animals; the 9-yo can kayak or paddleboard the quarry lake.'),
('Knoxville',2,'Afternoon','World''s Fair Park & Sunsphere','The city''s biggest splash pad plus the 360° Sunsphere deck — free and central.'),
('Knoxville',3,'Evening','Market Square','Pedestrian square with restaurants, splash fountains, and live music for dinner.'),
('St. Louis',0,'Morning','City Museum','Plan 3-4 hours — caves, 30+ slides, rooftop madness; go at open before it packs and both girls have peak energy.'),
('St. Louis',1,'Midday','Turtle Playground','Free giant climbable turtles by City Museum''s own creator, minutes away — pair them to cap the morning.'),
('St. Louis',2,'Afternoon','Saint Louis Zoo','Consistently a top US zoo and free admission; shady Forest Park setting for a calmer afternoon.'),
('St. Louis',3,'Evening','Ted Drewes Frozen Custard','The iconic Route 66 ''concrete'' — so thick they hand it to you upside-down.'),
('Louisville',0,'Morning','Louisville Mega Cavern','Underground tram is all-ages; the 9-yo (age 7+) can do the underground zipline while the 5-yo rides along.'),
('Louisville',1,'Midday','Kentucky Science Center','Three floors of hands-on plus a toddler zone splits the ages perfectly on a hot afternoon.'),
('Louisville',2,'Afternoon','Falls of the Ohio State Park','Walk exposed fossil beds and do the Fossil Challenge scavenger hunt — hands-on wonder for both.'),
('Louisville',3,'Evening','Waterfront Park + Big Four Bridge','Free playgrounds and splash pad, then walk the bridge into Indiana at sunset.'),
('Cincinnati',0,'Morning','Cincinnati Zoo','Meet Fiona the hippo early; the botanical setting is one of the best-ranked in the country.'),
('Cincinnati',1,'Midday','Newport Aquarium','Cross the river to walk the 75-ft Shark Bridge rope walk over sharks — thrilling for the 9-yo, penguins for the 5-yo.'),
('Cincinnati',2,'Afternoon','Smale Riverfront Park','Free fountains, an adventure playground, and a carousel to burn energy riverside.'),
('Cincinnati',3,'Evening','Newport on the Levee / Box Park','Open-air shipping-container food park right by the aquarium — easy dinner.'),
('Columbus',0,'Morning','Columbus Zoo and Aquarium','Jack Hanna''s zoo plus a manatee coast and aquarium — arrive at open to beat both crowds and heat.'),
('Columbus',1,'Midday','Zoombezi Bay','The award-winning water park is right at the zoo (summer) — wave pool and slides for a hot midday.'),
('Columbus',2,'Afternoon','COSI','300k sq ft of hands-on science and a T. rex dino gallery — an indoor, energy-flexible afternoon.'),
('Columbus',3,'Evening','North Market','Historic 1876 food hall where Jeni''s Ice Cream was born — a vendor for every taste.'),
('Indianapolis',0,'Morning','Children''s Museum of Indianapolis','World''s largest — hit Dinosphere and the real fossil labs at open; easily a half-day for both ages.'),
('Indianapolis',1,'Midday','Garfield Park Conservatory','A calm tropical glasshouse with a Children''s Garden — a green, low-key midday breather.'),
('Indianapolis',2,'Afternoon','Indianapolis Zoo','A rare zoo/aquarium/botanical combo with dolphins and orangutans; late-day when it cools.'),
('Indianapolis',3,'Evening','Canal Walk & White River SP','Pedal boats and the Colts Canal Playground on a flat waterside loop to end the day.'),
('Washington DC',0,'Morning','Nat''l Air & Space Museum','Newly renovated galleries; touch a moon rock. Free but reserve a timed entry the moment they release.'),
('Washington DC',1,'Midday','Nat''l Museum of Natural History','Dinosaur hall plus a live Insect Zoo and Butterfly Pavilion — hands-on and steps up the Mall.'),
('Washington DC',2,'Afternoon','Smithsonian''s National Zoo','Free with a timed ticket — pandas are back and there''s a new elephant calf.'),
('Washington DC',3,'Evening','Gravelly Point Park','Lie on the lawn while jets roar overhead landing at Reagan — pure, free delight to end the day.'),
('Williamsburg',0,'Morning','Colonial Williamsburg','Costumed trades, carriage rides, and a boxwood maze; go early before midday heat on the open streets. Kids often free in summer.'),
('Williamsburg',1,'Midday','Merchants Square dining','Walkable brick district right beside the historic area — bistro to tacos plus ice cream for a reset.'),
('Williamsburg',2,'Afternoon','Busch Gardens Williamsburg','Land of the Dragons and Sesame Street for the 5-yo, coasters for the 9-yo; ages 3-5 ride free.'),
('Williamsburg',3,'Evening','Yorktown Beach & Riverwalk','A gentle river beach and walkable waterfront with a free trolley to wind down.'),
('Pittsburgh',0,'Morning','Carnegie / Kamin Science Center','Five floors of 100+ hands-on exhibits plus a real submarine kids can board — start when doors open.'),
('Pittsburgh',1,'Midday','Children''s Museum of Pittsburgh','Voted #1 US children''s museum (''26) — open-ended, tinker-heavy play right across the North Side.'),
('Pittsburgh',2,'Afternoon','Duquesne Incline','Ride the 1877 cable railway up Mt. Washington for the iconic three-rivers view — a quick thrill both love.'),
('Pittsburgh',3,'Evening','Randyland','A free, joyfully weird folk-art courtyard on the North Side to explore before dinner.'),
('Philadelphia',0,'Morning','The Franklin Institute','Three floors of hands-on science and the walk-through two-story Giant Heart — a classic for both ages.'),
('Philadelphia',1,'Midday','Reading Terminal Market','Historic covered market — Amish pretzels and dozens of vendors for a pick-your-own lunch.'),
('Philadelphia',2,'Afternoon','Philadelphia Zoo','America''s first zoo, with Zoo360 mesh trails that let animals roam overhead — magic for kids.'),
('Philadelphia',3,'Evening','Franklin Square','Carousel, mini-golf, and a fountain show — a free, relaxed cap to a big day.'),
('Savannah',0,'Morning','Tybee Island Marine Science Center','Touch tanks, live sea turtles, and a pirate-ship playground right on the sand — great first stop on Tybee.'),
('Savannah',1,'Midday','Tybee Island Beach & Pier','Wide, gentle-surf beach for shelling and splashing — stay out on the island for the midday hours.'),
('Savannah',2,'Afternoon','Dolphin Adventure Boat Tour','A small-boat cruise to spot wild bottlenose dolphins — the afternoon light is good for it.'),
('Savannah',3,'Evening','Forsyth Park','The iconic fountain, two playgrounds, and summer sprinklers back in town for a wind-down.'),
('Charleston',0,'Morning','South Carolina Aquarium','Touch tank, the 385k-gal Great Ocean Tank, and a live Sea Turtle Recovery hospital — go at open on the harbor.'),
('Charleston',1,'Midday','Shem Creek Park & Boardwalk','A marsh boardwalk where dolphins work the creek beside shrimp boats — walkable and often free.'),
('Charleston',2,'Afternoon','Isle of Palms','The most family-friendly beach — wide sand, calmer waves, lifeguards for the afternoon.'),
('Charleston',3,'Evening','Joe Riley Waterfront Park','The Pineapple Fountain doubles as a free downtown splash pad to rinse off the day.'),
('St. Augustine',0,'Morning','St. Augustine Alligator Farm','Hundreds of gators, a bird rookery, and lemurs; the 9-yo can zip line over live crocs while the 5-yo watches.'),
('St. Augustine',1,'Midday','Castillo de San Marcos','Kids climb the ramparts of America''s oldest masonry fort; time it for a cannon demo. Free under 16.'),
('St. Augustine',2,'Afternoon','Anastasia State Park','1,600 acres of uncrowded beach plus a calm tidal lagoon for first-time kayaking — cool off here.'),
('St. Augustine',3,'Evening','Colonial Quarter','Living-history village with blacksmiths and a climbable watchtower before dinner in the old town.'),
('Orlando',0,'Morning','Aquatica','The animal-lover''s water park — a slide passes right through a ray tank; all-ages and gentler than the mega-parks. (Check: Volcano Bay is closed Oct 26 ''26–Mar 24 ''27.)'),
('Orlando',1,'Midday','LEGOLAND Florida + Water Park','Rides scaled exactly to ages 2-10 — nobody ages out, nobody''s scared. A calmer alternative day if you want dry rides.'),
('Orlando',2,'Afternoon','Gatorland','The anti-mega-park — a 110-acre gator preserve with boardwalks and zip lines, easy afternoon pace.'),
('Orlando',3,'Evening','Blue Spring State Park','In winter (mid-Nov–March) hundreds of wild manatees huddle here; boardwalk viewing 40 min off the grid.'),
('Tampa / St. Pete',0,'Morning','Mote SEA','The brand-new (''25) aquarium with a 400k-gal Gulf habitat overhead — go to UTC, NOT the closed old City Island site.'),
('Tampa / St. Pete',1,'Midday','The Florida Aquarium','Downtown and hands-on; pairs perfectly with the Riverwalk if you want a second marine stop.'),
('Tampa / St. Pete',2,'Afternoon','Sunken Gardens','A 100-year-old sunken tropical garden with flamingos in walkable St. Pete — a calm, shaded afternoon.'),
('Tampa / St. Pete',3,'Evening','Great Explorations','Hands-on and ''designed for 10 and under'' — an easy energy-burner near Sunken Gardens before dinner.'),
('Nature Coast (Crystal River)',0,'Morning','Swim with Manatees — Three Sisters Springs','The only legal wild-manatee swim in the US; book an early guided tour (Nov 15–Mar 31) when the water''s calmest.'),
('Nature Coast (Crystal River)',1,'Midday','Ellie Schiller Homosassa Springs','Walk underwater into the ''Fish Bowl'' for face-to-glass manatees year-round plus a wildlife boardwalk — the off-season backup.'),
('Nature Coast (Crystal River)',2,'Afternoon','Weeki Wachee Springs','The legendary underwater mermaid show plus Buccaneer Bay spring slides (summer) for the girls to cool off.'),
('Nature Coast (Crystal River)',3,'Evening','Giraffe Ranch','Feed giraffes from a safari truck on a 47-acre preserve — reservation-only, a memorable wind-down if booked ahead.'),
('Charlotte',0,'Morning','U.S. National Whitewater Center','Arrive at opening while it''s cool; free trails first, then a guided family raft trip.'),
('Charlotte',1,'Midday','U.S. National Whitewater Center','Lunch riverside at the Center''s grill so nobody loses momentum.'),
('Charlotte',2,'Afternoon','Daniel Stowe Botanical Garden','Shady paths and a fountain the 5-yo can splash in, ~20 min west in Belmont.'),
('Charlotte',3,'Evening','Freedom Park & Little Sugar Creek Greenway','Feed the ducks and burn off energy on the greenway loop before dinner.'),
('Gatlinburg / Pigeon Forge',0,'Morning','Cades Cove Loop','Enter at dawn for the best shot at black bears and deer before crowds and heat build.'),
('Gatlinburg / Pigeon Forge',1,'Midday','Sugarlands Visitor Center & Salamander Creeks','Cool off creekside on the flat Fighting Creek trail; grab Junior Ranger booklets for the girls.'),
('Gatlinburg / Pigeon Forge',2,'Afternoon','Ripley''s Aquarium of the Smokies','Beat afternoon storms indoors; the glass shark tunnel and stingray touch tank are AC-cooled hits.'),
('Gatlinburg / Pigeon Forge',3,'Evening','The Island in Pigeon Forge','Free splash fountains let the 5-yo run wild while the family rides the Wheel at sunset and grabs dinner.'),
('NC Triangle (Raleigh–Durham)',0,'Morning','Museum of Life and Science','Arrive at 10 open; ride the train to the bears and lemurs before the heat and crowds build.'),
('NC Triangle (Raleigh–Durham)',1,'Midday','Sarah P. Duke Gardens','Picnic and feed the koi; shady terraces give the little one a stroller-nap window.'),
('NC Triangle (Raleigh–Durham)',2,'Afternoon','Duke Lemur Center','Book a mid-afternoon tour weeks ahead — it''s reservation-only and the marquee memory.'),
('NC Triangle (Raleigh–Durham)',3,'Evening','Durham Bulls Baseball','Dollar-dog dinner at the ballpark; leave after the fireworks or the 7th if bedtime looms.')) v(ci,o,wl,st,nt) join cities c on c.name=v.ci;

